7–Male":"1337–Deceased","1339–Female":"1339–Deceased","1330–1425":"1330–1425","1360–1461":"1360–1461","1286–1366":"1286–1366","1300–1394":"1300–1394","1286":"1286","1330":"1330","1461":"1461","1394":"1394","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1425":"1425","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","1422":"1422","1366":"1366","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1353":"1353","1331":"1331","1339":"1339","Calne, Calne, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Calne, Wiltshire, England","Calne, Wiltshire, England":"Calne, Wiltshire, England","Calne, England, United Kingdom":"Calne, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Blake","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish (England and central Scotland): variant of   Black   1, meaning ‘swarthy’ or ‘dark-haired’, from a byform of the Old English adjective <i>blæc</i>, <i>blac</i> ‘black’, with change of vowel length.","English: nickname from Middle English <i>blak(e)</i> (Old English <i>blāc</i>) ‘wan, pale, white, fair’. In Middle English the two words <i>blac</i> and <i>blāc</i>, with opposite meanings, fell together as Middle English <i>blake</i>. In the absence of independent evidence as to whether the person referred to was dark or fair, it is now impossible to tell which sense was originally meant.","English (Norfolk): nickname from Middle English <i>bleik</i>, <i>blaik</i>&gt;, <i>blek(e)</i> (Old Norse <i>bleikr</i>) ‘pale or sallow’ (in complexion)."],"variants":[{"name":"Bleak","meanings":["English: mostly a variant of   Blake  , but perhaps also of   Blick  . This form of the surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Black","meanings":["English and Scottish: chiefly from Middle English <i>blak(e)</i> ‘black’ (Old English <i>blæc</i>, <i>blaca</i>), a nickname given from the earliest times to a swarthy or dark-haired man. However, Middle English <i>blac</i> also meant ‘pale, wan’, a reflex of Old English <i>blāc</i> ‘pale, white’ with a shortened vowel. Compare   Blatch   and   Blick  . With rare exceptions it is impossible to disambiguate these antithetical senses in Middle English surnames. The same difficulty arises with   Blake   and   Block  .","Scottish: in Gaelic-speaking areas this name was adopted as a translation of the epithet <i>dubh</i> ‘dark, black-(haired)’, or of various other names based on Gaelic <i>dubh</i> ‘black’, see   Duff  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of various European surnames directly or indirectly derived from the adjective meaning ‘black, dark’, for example German and Jewish   Schwarz   and Slavic surnames beginning with <i>Čern-</i>, <i>Chern-</i> (see   Chern   and   Cherne  ), <i>Chorn-</i>, <i>Crn-</i> or <i>Czern-</i>."]},{"name":"Blaikie","meanings":["Scottish: nickname from a pet form of   Blake  ."]},{"name":"Blakes","meanings":["English: variant of   Blake  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":2,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":47,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry Blake was born in 1335, in Calne, Wiltshire, England, his father, Robert Blake VII, was 49 and his mother, Anne Cole, was 35. He married Elizabeth Durant in 1353, in Calne, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1422, in his hometown, at the age of 87, and was buried in Calne, Wiltshire, England."},"et":{"1335–1422":"1335–1422","1337–Male":"1337–Surnud","1339–Female":"1339–Surnud","1330–1425":"1330–1425","1360–1461":"1360–1461","1286–1366":"1286–1366","1300–1394":"1300–1394","1286":"1286","1330":"1330","1461":"1461","1394":"1394","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1425":"1425","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","1422":"1422","1366":"1366","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1353":"1353","1331":"1331","1339":"1339","Calne, Calne, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Calne, Wiltshire, England","Calne, Wiltshire, England":"Calne, Wiltshire, England","Calne, England, United Kingdom":"Calne, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1335–1422":"1335–1422","1337–Male":"1337–Kuollut","1339–Female":"1339–Kuollut","1330–1425":"1330–1425","1360–1461":"1360–1461","1286–1366":"1286–1366","1300–1394":"1300–1394","1286":"1286","1330":"1330","1461":"1461","1394":"1394","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1425":"1425","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","1422":"1422","1366":"1366","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1353":"1353","1331":"1331","1339":"1339","Calne, Calne, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Calne, Wiltshire, England","Calne, Wiltshire, England":"Calne, Wiltshire, England","Calne, England, United Kingdom":"Calne, Wiltshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1335–1422":"1335–1422","1337–Male":"1337–Décédé","1339–Female":"1339–Décéd